\begin_layout Title
Completing the Square
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Evan Russenberger-Rosica
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Completing the square is a method for converting a quadratic polynomial
 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 to the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(x+h\right)^{2}+k$
\end_inset

.
 It is useful is both elementary algebra and higher mathematics.
 In this article, we attempt to create a deep understanding of completing
 the square starting from first principles.
 We begin with a brief introduction to the concept of factoring and review
 the grouping method and its shortcomings.
 We then discuss how to complete the square and illustrate how it can be
 used to derive the quadratic formula.
 We conclude with a geometric visualization of completing the square as
 well as a brief comparison to other factoring methods.
 Several exercises are then provided for the reader.
\end_layout

