\begin_layout Section
Introduction to Factoring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Factoring
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
factorization
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the process of writing a number or another mathematical object as a
 product of several 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
factors
\end_layout

\end_inset

, usually smaller or simpler objects of the same kind.
 In other words, factoring a mathematical object is the process of decomposing
 it into smaller parts (the factors), which when multiplied together, result
 in the original object.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2\times5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $-4\times-5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10\times2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $20\times1$
\end_inset

 are some factorization of the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $20$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We factor numbers every day without even realizing it.
 For example, if you walk into a bank and ask to withdraw 
\begin_inset Formula $\$120$
\end_inset

 from your account in denominations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\$20$
\end_inset

, the teller should hand you 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\$20$
\end_inset

 bills.
 A prudent person might then double check that 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times20=120$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 check that 
\begin_inset Formula $6\times20$
\end_inset

 is a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $120$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as we can factor numbers, we can also factor polynomials, i.e.
 we can break them up into simpler factors, which when multiplied together
 give us back the original expression.
 In this document, we will focus on factoring quadratic polynomials.
 Recall that a 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
quadratic polynomial
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax^{2}+bx+c
\]

\end_inset

Some quadratic polynomials are easy to factor.
 For example 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-4$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
difference of two squares
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and so it can be factored as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+2\right)\left(x-2\right)$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "exer:diff-of-two-squares"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, not all polynomials are so easy to factor.
 In the following sections will will discuss and compare three methods for
 factoring polynomials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Factoring via the Grouping Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We often try to factor an expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 by finding two numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta=b$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we're trying to find two numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 which multiply to give 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and add to give 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 We can then factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+c=\left(x+\alpha\right)\left(x+\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 .
 This is known as the 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
grouping method
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 But why does the grouping method work? Working backwards from the factored
 expression we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(x+\alpha\right)\left(x+\beta\right) & =x\left(x+\beta\right)+a\left(x+\beta\right)\\
 & =x^{2}+\beta x+\alpha x+\alpha\beta\\
 & =x^{2}+\left(\alpha+\beta\right)x+\alpha\beta\\
 & =x^{2}+bx+c
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we see how by making the substitutions 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+c=\left(x+\alpha\right)\left(x+\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 .
 One advantage of such a factorization is it allows us to easily find all
 solutions (zeros) of this polynomial.
 Unfortunately, factoring in this manner is not always possible as we will
 see in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "exa:Factor-grouping-fail"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-8x+16$
\end_inset

 using the grouping method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We need to find two numbers that multiply to 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

 and add to 
\begin_inset Formula $-8$
\end_inset

.
 We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-4\right)^{2}=16$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-4+-4=-8$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-8x+16=\left(x-4\right)\left(x-4\right)=\left(x-4\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-8x+15$
\end_inset

 using the grouping method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We need to find two numbers that multiply to 
\begin_inset Formula $15$
\end_inset

 and add to 
\begin_inset Formula $-8$
\end_inset

.
 We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $-3\times-5=15$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-3+-5=-8$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-8x+15=\left(x-3\right)\left(x-5\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:Factor-grouping-fail"

\end_inset

Factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-8x+17$
\end_inset

 using the grouping method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
We need two numbers which multiply to 
\begin_inset Formula $17$
\end_inset

 and add to 
\begin_inset Formula $-8$
\end_inset

.
 But 17 is a prime number, so the only pairs of integers that multiply to
 give 
\begin_inset Formula $17$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $(17,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(-17,-1)$
\end_inset

, which do not add to 
\begin_inset Formula $-8$
\end_inset

.
 We could try to guess two non-integers which multiply to 
\begin_inset Formula $17$
\end_inset

 and sum to 
\begin_inset Formula $-8$
\end_inset

, however this is very difficult, so we need to find a better method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Factoring via Completing the Square
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
In elementary algebra, 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
completing the square
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a technique for converting a quadratic polynomial of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax^{2}+bx+c
\]

\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\left(x+h\right)^{2}+k
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is known as the 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
constant term
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:complete-the-arbitrary-square"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we will show 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{c}{a}-\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:We-can-factor"

\end_inset

We can factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 That is to say:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+bx+\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}=\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We can observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 does factor to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 by factoring it using the grouping method.
 So we want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta=\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta=b$
\end_inset

.
 We observe that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\beta$
\end_inset

 then we can solve explicitly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha\beta & =\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}\\
\alpha^{2} & =\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}\\
\sqrt{\alpha^{2}} & =\sqrt{\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}}\\
\alpha & =\frac{b}{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\beta=\frac{b}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We can also check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\beta=\frac{b}{2}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta=b$
\end_inset

.
 Sure enough 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha+\beta & =\alpha+\alpha\\
 & =2\alpha\\
 & =2\frac{b}{2}\\
 & =b
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:add-zero-trick"

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

add-zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trick
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

add-zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trick is a useful algebraic tool that involves rewriting an expression
 by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-b$
\end_inset

 to the same expression simultaneously.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $b+\left(-b\right)=0$
\end_inset

, using this trick does not change the value of the expression.
 That is, for any numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 it is true that easily.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a & =a+b-b\\
 & =a+0\\
 & =a
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Rewrite the function 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

add-zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trick with some number 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax^{2}+bx+c=ax^{2}+bx+c+d-d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:adding-b/2"

\end_inset

An expression of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx$
\end_inset

, can be factored into the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

add-zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trick (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:add-zero-trick"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to simultaneously add 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx$
\end_inset

 and then apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:We-can-factor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to factor the resulting expression.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+bx & =x^{2}+bx+\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
monic
\end_layout

\end_inset

 quadratic polynomial is a quadratic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.
 it has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:completing-the-monic"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 be a monic quadratic polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+bx+c=\left(x-h\right)^{2}+k
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=c-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This is very similar to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:adding-b/2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, except that we now have a constant term 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in the initial equation.
 However, everything else is the same and we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is eventually just absorbed into the constant term 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+bx+c & =x^{2}+bx+\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}+c\\
 & =\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}+c\\
 & =\left(x+\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}+k^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $k=c-\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, the result is proved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we relax (i.e.
 eliminate) the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 may represent an arbitrary quadratic polynomial.
 In the next theorem, we show how to rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c=0$
\end_inset

 by completing the square.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:complete-the-arbitrary-square"

\end_inset

By completing the square, we can factor an arbitrary quadratic polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ax^{2}+bx+c=\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-k
\]

\end_inset

with constant term 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{c}{a}-\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We begin by factoring out 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

from the first two terms.
 This simplifies the algebra somewhat vs if we had factored 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 out of all three terms.
 We then use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

add-zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trick to add 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the expression.
 We then then apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:We-can-factor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to factor the resulting expression, thus 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

completing the square
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ax^{2}+bx+c & =a\left[x^{2}+\frac{b}{a}x\right]+c\\
 & =a\left[x^{2}+\frac{b}{a}x+\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}\right]+c\\
 & =a\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-a\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}+c\\
 & =a\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{4a}+c\\
 & =a\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}+k
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the constant term 
\begin_inset Formula $k=-\frac{b^{2}}{4a}+c$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have completed the square on an arbitrary quadratic polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

, we can solve this expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, thereby obtaining the a formula for the solutions of an arbitrary quadratic
 polynomial.
 This is known as the 
\begin_inset Flex definition
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
quadratic formula
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Quadratic Formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Quadratic-Formula"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary quadratic formula.
 Then the two solutions (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roots
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We take the factorization of an arbitrary quadratic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $ax^{2}+bx+c$
\end_inset

 obtained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:complete-the-arbitrary-square"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}-\frac{b^{2}}{4a}+c & =0\\
a\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2} & =\frac{b^{2}}{4a}-c\\
\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2} & =\frac{b^{2}}{4a^{2}}-\frac{c}{a}\\
\sqrt{\left(x+\frac{b}{2a}\right)^{2}} & =\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4a^{2}}-\frac{c}{a}}\\
x+\frac{b}{2a} & =\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4a^{2}}-\frac{c}{a}}\\
x & =\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}}{4a^{2}}-\frac{c}{a}}-\frac{b}{2a}\\
 & =\sqrt{\frac{b^{2}-4ac}{4a^{2}}}-\frac{b}{2a}\\
 & =\frac{\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}-\frac{b}{2a}\\
 & =\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

