\end_inset

We often apply multiple translations to a single function.
 For example, we might scale 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 vertically and horizontally, or we might flip it vertically and shift it
 horizontally.
 We might even apply all four translations to a single graph.
 How do we approach finding the shape of the translated graph? The key insight
 is that each translation can be applied one by one, in any order and the
 result will be the same.
 For example, flipping the graph vertically, then shifting it horizontally
 is the same as shifting it and then flipping it.
 Thus we may break apart a complex translation into a composition of simple
 translations and compute the simple translations in any way we like.
 We will take advantage of this property in the next section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Application to Completing the Square
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Keeping in mind what we have learned about graph translations, what does
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(x+h\right)^{2}+k$
\end_inset

 look like relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

? In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

, how does 
\begin_inset Formula $af\left(x+h\right)+k$
\end_inset

 transform it? It is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Vertically stretched/shrunk by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Horizontally shifted to the left by 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Vertically shifted by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 has a vertex of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $af\left(x+h\right)+k$
\end_inset

 has its vertex at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-h,k\right)$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=8x^{2}-64x+16$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rewrite 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 by completing the square
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-8x^{2}-64x+16 & =-8\left[x^{2}+8x\right]+16\\
 & =-8\left[x^{2}+8x+16-16\right]+16\\
 & =-8\left[\left(x+4\right)^{2}-16\right]+16\\
 & =-8\left(x+4\right)^{2}+8\cdot16+16\\
 & =-8\left(x+4\right)^{2}+9\cdot16\\
 & =-8\left(x+4\right)^{2}+144
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 in terms of graph translations from 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
